# Trivy CVE allowlist ‚Äî keep tight, document every entry.
#
# Each block follows the same pattern : the CVE id, the *binary* it
# affects in our image, the reason we can't fix it at our layer, and
# what we'd track to remove the exception later.
#
# Rule of thumb : only ignore CVEs in code we vendor through a
# third-party (Chrome via puppeteer, browser engines, etc.). Anything
# in our own dependency tree gets patched via `pnpm.overrides` instead.
#
# Note : `app/node_modules/` is fully skipped from the Trivy scan via
# the workflow's `skip-dirs:` input ‚Äî `pnpm audit --audit-level=high`
# in the CI typecheck step is the source of truth for npm vulns.
# Anything you'd put here for an api/web npm package should land in
# `pnpm.auditConfig.ignoreGhsas` (in the root `package.json`) instead.

# ---------------------------------------------------------------------
# picomatch CVE-2026-33671 inside pnpm's bundled distribution
# ---------------------------------------------------------------------
# Our own dependency tree pins `picomatch ‚â• 4.0.4` via
# `pnpm.overrides`. But the pnpm binary itself (resolved by
# `corepack enable`) ships a vendored picomatch 4.0.3 inside
# `/root/.cache/node/corepack/.../pnpm/<v>/dist/node_modules/picomatch`.
# That copy lives outside the `app/node_modules` tree the workflow
# skips, so Trivy still finds it and we need this ignore explicitly.
#
# Blast radius : pnpm runs at container start (`db:migrate &&
# start`) over our own lockfile, never against attacker-controlled
# globs. The CVE (RegexDoS via crafted extglob patterns) is
# unreachable through our HTTP surface.
#
# Drop criterion : when pnpm vendors picomatch ‚â• 4.0.4 in a
# corepack-distributed release. Track on each pnpm bump in
# `package.json` ‚Üí `packageManager`.
CVE-2026-33671

# ---------------------------------------------------------------------
# libexpat CVE-2026-45186 inside the nginx:alpine base image
# ---------------------------------------------------------------------
# `packages/web/Dockerfile` uses `nginx:alpine` as the runtime base.
# Alpine shipped the fix in libexpat 2.8.1-r0 ; the nginx:alpine
# snapshot we pull still carries 2.7.5-r0. The next nginx:alpine
# rebuild picks it up ‚Äî the libxml2 / openssl entries that used to sit
# here went through exactly this and were dropped once the image caught
# up (libxml2 2.13.9-r1, libcrypto3/libssl3 3.5.7-r0 now ship in base).
#
# Blast radius : libexpat is the Expat XML parser linked by nginx. Our
# vhost (`packages/web/nginx.conf`) only serves static assets + proxies
# `/api` ‚Äî no XML body parsing reaches the parser, so the DoS-via-XML
# vuln is unreachable through our surface.
#
# Drop criterion : when `nginx:alpine` ships libexpat ‚â• 2.8.1-r0
# (verify with `docker pull nginx:alpine && docker run --rm
# nginx:alpine apk info libexpat`).
CVE-2026-45186

# ---------------------------------------------------------------------
# pnpm itself (the pinned `packageManager`) ‚Äî build/start-time only
# ---------------------------------------------------------------------
# `packages/api/Dockerfile` is single-stage node:24-alpine, so the
# corepack-resolved pnpm (pinned `pnpm@10.33.0` in the root
# package.json `packageManager`) ships in the runtime image and Trivy
# flags it via the `package.json` scanner. Every one of these is a
# "pnpm processes a MALICIOUS package / manifest / lockfile /
# configDependency" class bug : arbitrary file write-delete, transitive
# alias path traversal, manifest-identity spoof bypassing allowBuilds,
# repo-controlled configDependencies, patch-remove file deletion,
# env-lockfile short-circuit.
#
# Blast radius : in our image pnpm runs exactly twice and only over OUR
# OWN committed inputs ‚Äî `pnpm install --frozen-lockfile` at build (our
# lockfile), then `pnpm db:migrate:docker && pnpm start:docker` at
# container start (no install at all). It never resolves an attacker-
# controlled package/manifest ; anyone who could inject one already owns
# the repo. None of these is reachable through the running app's HTTP
# surface.
#
# Drop criterion : bump pnpm to ‚â• 11.8.0 (the first line that fixes ALL
# of these ‚Äî several, e.g. CVE-2026-55697, have NO 10.x backport) in a
# dedicated upgrade PR where the lockfile + major bump get tested, then
# delete this whole block.
CVE-2026-50015
CVE-2026-50016
CVE-2026-55487
CVE-2026-55697
CVE-2026-55698
GHSA-72r4-9c5j-mj57
GHSA-fr4h-3cph-29xv
GHSA-qrv3-253h-g69c
